verdict.evidence:
All four load-bearing values are verified directly from the mosh source at commit decd9b7:

**SRTT_TRIGGER_HIGH = 30** ([terminaloverlay.h:216](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/mobile-shell/mosh@decd9b705eb81626f694335b8d5940538beb06da/-/blob/src/frontend/terminaloverlay.h?L216)):
```cpp
static const uint64_t SRTT_TRIGGER_HIGH = 30; /* > ms starts SRTT trigger */
```

**srtt_trigger gate in cull()** ([terminaloverlay.cc:434](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/mobile-shell/mosh@decd9b705eb81626f694335b8d5940538beb06da/-/blob/src/frontend/terminaloverlay.cc?L434)):
```cpp
if ( send_interval > SRTT_TRIGGER_HIGH ) {
    srtt_trigger = true;
} else if ( srtt_trigger && ( send_interval <= SRTT_TRIGGER_LOW ) && ( !active() ) ) {
    srtt_trigger = false;
}
```
Strict greater-than: `send_interval` must exceed 30, not merely reach it.

**SEND_INTERVAL_MIN = 20** ([transportsender.h:49](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/mobile-shell/mosh@decd9b705eb81626f694335b8d5940538beb06da/-/blob/src/network/transportsender.h?L49)):
```cpp
const int SEND_INTERVAL_MIN = 20;       /* ms between frames */
```

**send_interval() formula** ([transportsender-impl.h:63](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/mobile-shell/mosh@decd9b705eb81626f694335b8d5940538beb06da/-/blob/src/network/transportsender-impl.h?L63)):
```cpp
int SEND_INTERVAL = lrint( ceil( connection->get_SRTT() / 2.0 ) );
if ( SEND_INTERVAL < SEND_INTERVAL_MIN ) {
    SEND_INTERVAL = SEND_INTERVAL_MIN;
}
```
For SRTT = 1ms: ceil(0.5) = 1 → clamped to 20. For SRTT = 10ms: ceil(5.0) = 5 → clamped to 20. Any SRTT below 40ms yields send_interval = 20ms.

**apply() render gate for Adaptive mode** ([terminaloverlay.cc:352](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/mobile-shell/mosh@decd9b705eb81626f694335b8d5940538beb06da/-/blob/src/frontend/terminaloverlay.cc?L352)):
```cpp
if ( ( display_preference == Never )
     || !( srtt_trigger || glitch_trigger || ( display_preference == Always )
           || ( display_preference == Experimental ) ) ) {
    return;
}
```
With `display_preference == Adaptive`, the condition simplifies to: render only if `srtt_trigger || glitch_trigger`. When `srtt_trigger = false` and `glitch_trigger = 0`, the function returns without rendering anything — predictions are fully suppressed.

**set_send_interval call site** ([stmclient.cc:305](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/mobile-shell/mosh@decd9b705eb81626f694335b8d5940538beb06da/-/blob/src/frontend/stmclient.cc?L305)):
```cpp
overlays.get_prediction_engine().set_send_interval( network->send_interval() );
```
Confirms the PredictionEngine's `send_interval` field is fed directly from `TransportSender::send_interval()`, so the clamping to 20ms is the actual value seen by the srtt_trigger logic.

**Chain of evidence on LAN (SRTT ~1ms):**
- `send_interval` = max(ceil(SRTT/2), 20) = 20ms
- 20 is NOT > 30 (SRTT_TRIGGER_HIGH) → `srtt_trigger` stays false
- With `display_preference == Adaptive`, `apply()` renders nothing (srtt_trigger=false, glitch_trigger=0)
- Conclusion: zero local echo on a typical LAN with Adaptive mode, except for glitch bursts (prediction pending ≥ 250ms → GLITCH_THRESHOLD)

**One precision note:** The claim says "sub-1ms LAN" but the conclusion holds for any SRTT below 40ms (since send_interval = SRTT/2 rounded up, clamped at 20; and 20 ≤ 30). Even a 39ms SRTT gives send_interval=20, still below the trigger. The trigger only fires at SRTT ≥ 61ms (send_interval = ceil(61/2) = 31 > 30).

**The claim is confirmed for the classic Remote-SSH server handshake path, but importantly incomplete because VS Code 1.99+ also runs a second, parallel protocol layer with different versioning.**

**Classic handshake (commit-hash-as-version — still current):**

In [`remoteAgentConnection.ts` lines 284–295](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/microsoft/vscode@7246c70399a331f4e613b5fb8e1e1905e9791dd6/-/blob/src/vs/platform/remote/common/remoteAgentConnection.ts#L284-295), the client sends a `ConnectionTypeRequest` JSON message with `commit: options.commit` (the desktop's commit SHA) in the WebSocket handshake. The server side in [`remoteExtensionHostAgentServer.ts` lines 335–342](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/microsoft/vscode@7246c70399a331f4e613b5fb8e1e1905e9791dd6/-/blob/src/vs/server/node/remoteExtensionHostAgentServer.ts#L335-342) does an exact equality check:

```typescript
const rendererCommit = msg2.commit;
const myCommit = this._productService.commit;
if (rendererCommit && myCommit) {
    if (rendererCommit !== myCommit) {
        return rejectWebSocketConnection(`Client refused: version mismatch`);
    }
}
```

This mechanism is unchanged in the current HEAD of the `microsoft/vscode` repo (commit `7246c70`). The glibc ≥ 2.28 change in 1.99 is a binary build compatibility requirement, not a protocol versioning change, and did not affect this commit-equality check.

**Binary download URL also commit-keyed:** [`sshRemoteAgentHostHelpers.ts` lines 168–178](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/microsoft/vscode@7246c70399a331f4e613b5fb8e1e1905e9791dd6/-/blob/src/vs/platform/agentHost/node/sshRemoteAgentHostHelpers.ts#L168-178) shows the CLI is fetched from `https://update.code.visualstudio.com/commit:<commitHash>/cli-<os>-<arch>/<quality>` and installed at `~/.vscode-server/<archive>-<commitHash>`, confirming the commit hash is the version key end-to-end.

**New Agent Host Protocol (post-1.99, separate layer — NOT commit-hash-based):** VS Code 1.99+ introduced a new Agent Host Protocol (AHP) layer. Its version registry ([`registry.ts` line 19](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/microsoft/vscode@7246c70399a331f4e613b5fb8e1e1905e9791dd6/-/blob/src/vs/platform/agentHost/common/state/protocol/version/registry.ts#L19)) defines `PROTOCOL_VERSION = '0.3.0'` — a proper SemVer string, not a commit hash. The `initialize` handshake sends `protocolVersions: ['0.3.0']` and the server does SemVer-caret negotiation. This layer is entirely independent of the commit-hash mechanism. The CLI tunnel protocol in `cli/src/constants.rs` uses an integer `PROTOCOL_VERSION: u32 = 5` separately.
